[start section id="20112"]

#1 Rectal cancer
#2 von Willebrand's disease
Mrs. Vargas is a 62-year-old woman who was diagnosed with rectal cancer after about one-year history of BRBPR and rectal discomfort.  At the time of diagnosis, she had a colonoscopy done and CT-scan of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis that did not reveal any evidence of lymphadenopathy or metastatic disease.  Unfortunately, we do not have information about the extent of her tumor at the time of diagnosis.  The patient states that one of the surgeons that she was seeing noted on exam that it has shrunk significantly with chemoradiation.  Following chemoradiation, the patient underwent surgical resection and on pathology, she was noted to have 1.4 x 0.4 x  0.4 tumor after lower anterior resection and with abdominal perineal resection, there was residual mass forming a 2.2 x 1.0 x 0.3 cm in the lower rectum.  Based on pathology, she was staged as pT2.  We can assume that given the shrinkage of the tumor and the invasion into muscularis propria currently, there was most likely a more significant extension or maybe node involvement prior to initiation of chemoradiation therapy.  Based on that uncertainty as well as the size of the tumor now, we would recommend treatment with adjuvant modified FOLFOX chemotherapy given for eight cycles to decrease her chance of local and distant recurrence.  We would recommend omitting the 5-FU bolus from the regimen. We discussed with the patient major side-effects of this treatment including nausea, rashes, hand-foot syndrome, fatigue, neuropathy with oxaliplatin, low blood counts, and others.  She will also need lab test and imaging studies at regular interval following treatment. The patient will follow-up for her chemotherapy closer to home with Dr Denson .
Regarding her von Willebrand's disease she did not have any bleeding post-op while on Humate- P treatment. She was followed by Hematology during her hospitalization.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

